The standalone table model is a robust framework designed to capture the essence of tabular data, operating independently of any external datasets. Within this model, tables are conceptualized as collections of rows and columns, each of which is modeled with its own set of probability distributions and covariances. These elements collectively form a descriptive model encapsulating the entire table's characteristics. The foundation of this model lies in understanding the distribution shapes of each column's values, which are delineated by cumulative distribution functions (CDFs). The choice of distribution, whether Gaussian, truncated Gaussian, uniform, beta, or exponential, hinges on statistical tests such as the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test, ensuring an optimal fit to the data. Parameters associated with each distribution type represent distinct statistics, enabling nuanced interpretation and modeling flexibility.

Moreover, covariance estimation, crucial for understanding the interdependence between columns, is conducted using the multivariate Gaussian Copula. This approach mitigates potential biases introduced by distribution shapes, ensuring accurate covariance estimation. The process involves transforming original distribution CDFs to standard normal form before computing the covariance matrix. By decoupling the covariance estimation from distribution shapes, the Gaussian Copula method provides a reliable means of capturing dependencies between columns. The resulting generative model comprises distribution parameters and the covariance matrix, encapsulating essential information from the original table in a compact yet comprehensive format. This model serves as a foundation for synthesizing new data that faithfully represents the underlying structure of the original dataset.

Conditional sampling, a feature inherent to the Gaussian Copula model, offers enhanced flexibility in data generation by allowing users to specify conditions for sampling. This functionality enables the generation of data that adheres to predefined constraints, facilitating the creation of synthetic datasets tailored to specific scenarios or requirements. Whether sampling from conditional distributions or specifying conditions for desired values, users can leverage this capability to generate data subsets that meet their criteria. By integrating conditional sampling into the standalone table model, the framework becomes more adaptable and versatile, catering to a diverse range of data generation needs across various domains and applications.
